## Why This Works

| Old Approach | Behavioral Approach |
|--------------|---------------------|
| 100+ word problem descriptions | 3-5 bullet points |
| 50+ tests covering every edge case | 4-6 behavioral tests |
| Tests None, limits, error codes | Tests "does feature work?" |
| You define entire API | AI must discover patterns |
| AI can pattern-match from verbose spec | AI must understand codebase |
| Tests dictate implementation | Tests verify outcomes |
| Single "correct" solution | Multiple valid approaches |

**Key insight:** Behavioral tests with acceptance criteria are HARDER for AI because:
- Can't game by pattern matching from verbose specs
- Must understand existing codebase patterns and philosophy
- Must reason about how feature integrates with existing code
- Must design internal architecture themselves
- No implementation hints to copy from
- Tests verify WHAT works, not HOW it's built
- Multiple valid solutions exist - AI must choose wisely

**The Test Suite Should:**
- Define correctness through observable behavior
- Allow creative implementation freedom
- Verify outcomes, not mechanisms
- Make naive/copy-paste implementations fail through edge cases
- Require deep understanding to pass all tests

